Interestingly, Entecavir is one of the rare examples of a rationally (although some might consider it irrationally!) designed nucleoside (Fig. 13
). In 1992, another carbocyclic nucleoside, Lobucavir, was garnering much attention, due to its potent antiviral activity against HBV and HSV (Marquez, 1996, Hayashi et al., 1990, Norbeck et al., 1990). Lobucavir possesses a cyclobutyl “sugar”, i.e. four-membered ring, and resembles the naturally occurring Oxetanocin G, which was isolated from bacteria in 1986 and later demonstrated antiviral activity against HIV (Fig. 14
). (Marquez, 1996)
